{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"4b8f11f5-faa5-4303-a188-ca73f4482dcc","content":"## What Happened\n\nC# 14 introduces **implicit span conversions** that change overload resolution. On .NET 10, `array.Contains(num)` now resolves to:\n\n```\nMemoryExtensions.Contains<int>(ReadOnlySpan<int>, int)\n```\n\ninstead of the .NET 9 resolution:\n\n```\nEnumerable.Contains<int>(IEnumerable<int>, int)\n```\n\nSince `ReadOnlySpan<T>` is a **ref struct**, it cannot be represented in expression trees. The expression tree interpreter fails at runtime when it encounters the span-based method call.\n\n## How to Fix\n\nDisambiguate by explicitly calling `Enumerable.Contains` (static-method syntax) or casting away the span conversion:\n\n**Option A — explicit static call:**\n```csharp\nExpression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =\n    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);\n```\n\n**Option B — cast to `IEnumerable<int>`:**\n```csharp\nExpression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =\n    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);\n```\n\nEither approach forces the compiler to bind to the `Enumerable` overload, which is expression-tree–safe.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"15326854-01a8-4c47-abc6-b73783a768d0","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a breaking change in .NET 10 / C# 14 that affects LINQ expression trees calling `.Contains()` on `int[]` arrays, specifically when using `preferInterpretation: true`.\n\nLet me think about what changed in .NET 10 / C# 14 that would cause this.\n\nIn C# 14 / .NET 10, there's a significant change related to extension members. C# 14 introduces **extension types** (formerly \"roles and extensions\"), but more relevantly, there's a change in how the compiler resolves `Contains()` on arrays.\n\nActually, let me think more carefully. \n\nIn .NET 9 and earlier, calling `array.Contains(num)` on an `int[]` resolves to the LINQ extension method `System.Linq.Enumerable.Contains<int>()`. But in .N